### Promises

A **Promise** represents a value that may be available **now, later, or never**. It is used for asynchronous operations.

---

### Promise States

| State | Meaning |
|-------|---------|
| **Pending** | Initial state, waiting for result |
| **Fulfilled** | Operation completed successfully |
| **Rejected** | Operation failed |
| **Settled** | Either fulfilled or rejected |

---

### Creating a Promise

```js
const myPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  let success = true;

  if (success) {
    resolve("Operation successful!");
  } else {
    reject("Operation failed!");
  }
});
```

---

### Using a Promise

```js
myPromise
  .then(result => console.log(result))   // On success
  .catch(error => console.error(error))  // On failure
  .finally(() => console.log("Done"));   // Always runs
```

---

### Real Example: Fetch API

```js
fetch("https://api.example.com/data")
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(error => console.error("Error:", error));
```

---

### Promise.all()

Wait for **multiple** promises:

```js
Promise.all([
  fetch(url1),
  fetch(url2),
  fetch(url3)
]).then(responses => {
  // All done!
});
```

> **Promises** solve "callback hell" by providing a cleaner chain structure for async code.

